In this assignment, students will be using the K-nearest neighbors algorithm to predict how many points NBA players scored in the 2013-2014 season.

A look at the data

Before we dive into the algorithm, lets take a look at our data. Each row in the data contains information on how a player performed in the 2013-2014 NBA season.

Download 'nba_2013.csv' file from this link: https://www.dropbox.com/s/b3nv38jjo5dxcl6/nba_2013.csv?dl=0

Here are some selected columns from the data: player - name of the player pos - the position of the player g - number of games the player was in gs - number of games the player started pts - total points the player scored

There are many more columns in the data, mostly containing information about average player game performance over the course of the season. See this site for an explanation of the rest of them: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/samsonqian/nba-2013

Industry method to predict pts in a season: Pythagorean Expectation (https://towardsdatascience.com/pythagorean-expectation-in-sports-analytics-with-examples-from-different-sports-f5e599530a6c)

lst_train_rmse = []
lst_train_score = []
lst_test_rmse = []
lst_test_score = []
lst_num_neighbors = []


for i in range(1, 21):
    print(f"NUMBER OF NEIGHBORS: {i}")
    knn = KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors=i, algorithm="auto")
    knn.fit(X_train_arr, y_train_arr)
    
    #train data metrics
    score_train = knn.score(X_train_arr, y_train_arr)
    print(f"Train Data model score: {score_train}")
    pred_y_train = knn.predict(X_train_arr)
    mse_train = mean_squared_error(y_train_arr, pred_y_train)
    rmse_train = math.sqrt(mse_train)
    print(f"Train Data RMSE: {rmse_train}")
    
    #test data metrics
    score_test = knn.score(X_test_arr, y_test_arr)
    print(f"Test Data model score: {score_test}")
    pred_y_test = knn.predict(X_test_arr)
    mse_test = mean_squared_error(y_test_arr, pred_y_test)
    rmse_test = math.sqrt(mse_test)
    print(f"Test Data RMSE: {rmse_test}")
    
    #save results
    lst_train_rmse.append(rmse_train)
    lst_train_score.append(score_train)
    lst_test_rmse.append(rmse_test)
    lst_test_score.append(score_test)
    lst_num_neighbors.append(i)
    
    #plot result (actual vs. pred)
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))
    plt.scatter(X_test_arr.flatten(), y_test_arr.flatten(), s=5, color="blue", label="original")
    plt.scatter(X_test_arr.flatten(), pred_y_test.flatten(), s=10, color="red", label="predicted")
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

lst_train_rmse_pca = []
lst_train_score_pca = []
lst_test_rmse_pca = []
lst_test_score_pca = []
lst_num_neighbors_pca = []


for i in range(1, 21):
    print(f"NUMBER OF NEIGHBORS: {i}")
    knn = KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors=i, algorithm="auto")
    knn.fit(pca_train, y_train_pca_arr)
    
    #train data metrics
    score_train = knn.score(pca_train, y_train_pca_arr)
    print(f"Train Data model score: {score_train}")
    pred_y_train = knn.predict(pca_train)
    mse_train = mean_squared_error(y_train_pca_arr, pred_y_train)
    rmse_train = math.sqrt(mse_train)
    print(f"Train Data RMSE: {rmse_train}")
    
    #test data metrics
    score_test = knn.score(pca_test, y_test_pca_arr)
    print(f"Test Data model score: {score_test}")
    pred_y_test = knn.predict(pca_test)
    mse_test = mean_squared_error(y_test_pca_arr, pred_y_test)
    rmse_test = math.sqrt(mse_test)
    print(f"Test Data RMSE: {rmse_test}")
    
    #save results
    lst_train_rmse_pca.append(rmse_train)
    lst_train_score_pca.append(score_train)
    lst_test_rmse_pca.append(rmse_test)
    lst_test_score_pca.append(score_test)
    lst_num_neighbors_pca.append(i)
    
    #plot result (actual vs. pred)
    pca_test_flattened = [pca_test[i][0] for i in range(len(pca_test))]
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))
    plt.scatter(pca_test_flattened, y_test_pca_arr.flatten(), s=5, color="blue", label="original")
    plt.scatter(pca_test_flattened, pred_y_test.flatten(), s=10, color="red", label="predicted")
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
